{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644413"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:05:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:05:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18046"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18046"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10760"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74129"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10760"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18046"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59620"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"10689"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25100"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25105"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74129"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the histological differences between resting chondrocytes and proliferating chondrocytes within bone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Resting chondrocytes are larger and isolated, while proliferating chondrocytes are small and clustered","Resting chondrocytes are flattened and arranged in clusters, while proliferating chondrocytes are spherical and isolated","Resting chondrocytes are larger and arranged in columns, while proliferating chondrocytes are small and round","Resting chondrocytes are small and round, while proliferating chondrocytes are larger and arranged in columns","Resting chondrocytes are spherical and isolated, while proliferating chondrocytes are flattened and arranged in clusters"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResting chondrocytes\u003C/strong\u003E are small, round cells located in the reserve zone of the growth plate. They are relatively inactive compared to proliferating chondrocytes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProliferating chondrocytes\u003C/strong\u003E are larger and flattened, and they are arranged in columns within the proliferative zone of the growth plate. This arrangement is crucial for the longitudinal growth of bones, as these cells divide and contribute to the lengthening of the bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe transition from resting to proliferating chondrocytes is a key process in bone growth and development, allowing for the continuous elongation of bones during childhood and adolescence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Resting chondrocytes are small, round, and located in the reserve zone of the growth plate.","Proliferating chondrocytes are larger, flattened, and arranged in columns in the proliferative zone.","The transition from resting to proliferating chondrocytes is crucial for bone growth and development."],"references":["Gartner, L. P. (2020). Textbook of histology e-book: Textbook of histology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Baig MA, Bacha D. Histology, Bone. 2023 May 1. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31082176","Blumer MJF. Bone tissue and histological and molecular events during development of the long bones. Ann Anat. 2021 May;235:151704. doi: 10.1016/j.aanat.2021.151704. Epub 2021 Feb 16. PMID: 33600952","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ,